The readings given below refer to sections in the course textbook:
[Amazon_logo] Howe, Roger, and Charles Sodini. Microelectronics: An Integrated
Approach. Upper Saddle River, NJ: Prentice Hall, 1996. ISBN: 9780135885185.
**** Abbreviations ****
MOS = metal-on-silicon
MOSFET = metal-oxide-semiconductor field-effect transistor
NMOS = n-type metal-oxide-semiconductor
CMOS = complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor
                               Course readings.
LECÂ TOPICS                                                      READINGS
       6.012 outline: grading, ethics
1      Overview of semiconductor applications, silicon integrated  2.5
       circuit technology
       Intrinsic semiconductors, electrons and holes, bond model,
2      generation recombination and thermal equilibrium; doping,   2.1-2.2
       donors, acceptors, compensation
3      Carrier transport, drift velocity, drift current density,   2.4
       diffusion current density
4      The p-n junction, carrier concentration and potential in    3.2-3.3
       thermal equilibrium, 60mV rule
5      The p-n junction in thermal equilibrium                     3.4
6      Introduction to the MOS structure, MOS capacitor in thermal 3.7
       equilibrium
7      MOS capacitor under applied bias; accumulation, depletion,  3.8
       and inversion regions
8      MOSFET physical structure, circuit symbol and terminal      4.1-4.3
       characteristics, MOS transistor characteristics
9      MOS transistor, backgate effect, MOSFET in saturation       4.4
10     MOSFET small-signal model                                   4.5
       Digital logic concepts, inverter characteristics, logic
11     levels and noise margins, transient characteristics,        5.1-5.2
       inverter circuits, NMOS/resistor loads
12     NMOS/current source load, CMOS inverter, static analysis    5.3-5.4
13     CMOS inverter, propagation delay model, static CMOS gates   5.5
14     p-n junction diode terminal characteristics, minority       6.1-6.3
       carrier concentration under forward and reverse bias
15     Short base approximation, steady state diffusion equation   6.3
       with currents in p-n junction
16     p-n junction diode circuit model, large signal static       6.4
       model, small signal model, diffusion capacitance
17     Introduction of bipolar junction transistor, terminal       7.1-7.2
       characteristics, forward active bias, current gain
18     Reverse active mode and saturation, the Ebers-Moll model    7.3-7.4
       Single stage amplifiers, two port small signal model,
19     common source amplifier with resistor and current source    8.1-8.6
       supply
20     Common base/gate amplifier, common collector/drain          8.8-8.9
21     Review frequency domain analysis; current gain frequency    10.1-10.3
       response of common emitter amplifier
       Voltage gain frequency response of common emitter
22     amplifier, full analysis of common emitter, the Miller      10.4
       approximation
23     Open circuit time constant analysis, common-gate (CG) and   10.5-10.6
       common-drain (CD) amplifiers
24     Multistage amplifiers, cascading small signal two port      9.1-9.2
       models
25     DC coupling, voltage sources, MOS current sources, current  9.4
       sources and sinks
26     Analyzing complex circuits and course wrap-up               9.6 and 10.7
